WEBVTT

00:02.700 --> 00:03.800
TOM:
Your company has been running up

00:03.800 --> 00:06.533
rather a lot of credit across
town.

00:06.533 --> 00:07.966
♪ ♪

00:07.966 --> 00:09.133
CLARA:
Even if we were to marry,

00:09.133 --> 00:10.566
the inheritance would still
go to her.

00:10.566 --> 00:11.700
EDWARD:
Don't you worry about Esther.

00:11.700 --> 00:12.900
I'm taking care of her.

00:12.900 --> 00:15.033
You're nothing but a coward!

00:15.033 --> 00:17.300
And you knew
and you said nothing.

00:17.300 --> 00:18.766
LENNOX:
You know what they say.

00:18.766 --> 00:19.966
All's fair in love and war.

00:19.966 --> 00:21.100
But then I've known both

00:21.100 --> 00:22.300
and you've known neither.

00:22.300 --> 00:23.466
COLBOURNE:
You are not to spend

00:23.466 --> 00:24.600
another minute in that man's
company.

00:24.600 --> 00:26.900
I'm not yours to order about.

00:26.900 --> 00:29.700
♪ ♪

00:31.233 --> 00:35.633
♪ ♪

00:41.166 --> 00:45.466
♪ ♪

00:51.266 --> 00:54.833
♪ ♪

00:56.166 --> 01:01.366
♪ ♪

01:16.233 --> 01:21.600
♪ ♪

01:26.033 --> 01:27.866
♪ ♪

01:27.866 --> 01:29.033
Ooh!

01:30.333 --> 01:32.533
Good morrow, horsey!

01:32.533 --> 01:36.733
♪ ♪

01:36.733 --> 01:38.633
Oh!

01:38.633 --> 01:42.833
ARTHUR:
Our ball looks set to be
a triumph!

01:42.833 --> 01:45.466
Almost all of London
joins us.

01:45.466 --> 01:47.833
I would not have
supposed it so popular.

01:48.700 --> 01:50.166
Come, shake off this gravity!

01:50.166 --> 01:51.900
With so many men of consequence,
any one of tonight's company

01:51.900 --> 01:53.300
could prove prospector.

01:53.300 --> 01:54.966
We could even dare to dream

01:54.966 --> 01:56.600
of escaping our debt to Eliza.

01:56.600 --> 01:58.466
Arthur,
the ball must be canceled.

01:59.966 --> 02:02.166
The shopkeepers say
they will not supply us.

02:02.166 --> 02:04.266
Not until the Army's debts
have been paid.

02:04.266 --> 02:05.333
But...

02:05.333 --> 02:07.266
They are even now
delivering supplies.

02:07.266 --> 02:10.300
No, they are taking them away.

02:10.300 --> 02:16.066
♪ ♪

02:23.433 --> 02:25.833
(birds twittering)

02:25.833 --> 02:29.600
ESTHER (voiceover):
It has been weeks
since your last letter.

02:30.733 --> 02:34.666
And I cannot account
for your silence.

02:36.633 --> 02:40.000
I beg you to put my mind
at rest.

02:42.200 --> 02:44.466
I'm taking Dr. Fuchs's tincture
to make me stronger

02:44.466 --> 02:48.066
so I can be the woman
you deserve.

02:48.066 --> 02:50.366
Please send word
that all is well.

02:52.166 --> 02:55.333
That you have not forgotten
your loving wife.

03:01.333 --> 03:03.033
ALISON:
I cannot stay here, Charlotte.

03:03.033 --> 03:05.466
I was willing to give him
my heart.

03:05.466 --> 03:06.733
My life.

03:06.733 --> 03:10.000
And in return, I almost drowned
on account of his lies.

03:10.000 --> 03:11.966
My mind is made up--
I leave tomorrow.

03:11.966 --> 03:13.500
What is left for me here?

03:13.500 --> 03:15.266
Your sister,
for one thing.

03:15.266 --> 03:17.433
My sister, the governess,
who I never see!

03:17.433 --> 03:19.366
But return with me!

03:19.366 --> 03:20.933
You cannot wish to work
a moment longer

03:20.933 --> 03:22.966
for Mr. Colbourne, given how
he spoke to you!

03:22.966 --> 03:25.433
I have a responsibility
to the girls.

03:26.733 --> 03:27.933
At least come to the ball,

03:27.933 --> 03:29.100
if it is to be our last night.

03:29.100 --> 03:31.566
So the whole town can laugh
at my folly.

03:31.566 --> 03:33.466
(slams)

03:33.466 --> 03:35.166
And he will be there.

03:35.166 --> 03:37.300
Alison...

03:44.200 --> 03:48.000
Whatever pain you feel now,
in time it will pass.

03:48.000 --> 03:51.900
The heart is more resilient
than you think.

03:51.900 --> 03:53.800
Indeed.

03:53.800 --> 03:57.066
I believe your own heart
is all but healed.

03:57.066 --> 03:59.866
That is why you wish
to stay in Sanditon.

04:01.633 --> 04:04.533
It is not for the sake
of the job or for the girls.

04:05.566 --> 04:07.900
It is for him.

04:07.900 --> 04:08.933
For whom?

04:08.933 --> 04:10.266
You cannot hide it
from your sister.

04:10.266 --> 04:12.866
I'm not trying to
hide anything.

04:12.866 --> 04:14.400
Unlike Captain Carter,

04:14.400 --> 04:17.866
Colonel Lennox
is a good man.

04:19.200 --> 04:22.366
One of us deserves
to find happiness.

04:25.100 --> 04:30.266
♪ ♪

04:35.866 --> 04:41.000
♪ ♪

04:44.366 --> 04:45.866
(knock at door)
BEATRICE:
Miss Lambe!

04:47.966 --> 04:50.233
♪ ♪

04:50.233 --> 04:54.466
Colonel Lennox will never make
good on the shopkeepers' debts.

04:54.466 --> 04:56.966
Not until I've repaid
mine to him.

04:56.966 --> 05:00.900
"Now is not the time to gamble,
Arthur."

05:00.900 --> 05:02.333
Those were your words.

05:02.333 --> 05:04.500
I know, I know,
but I got caught off-guard!

05:04.500 --> 05:06.700
I questioned his character
from the start

05:06.700 --> 05:09.200
and you made me feel foolish
for doubting him.

05:11.033 --> 05:12.700
Does Mary know?

05:17.166 --> 05:19.066
Then you must talk to her.

05:19.066 --> 05:20.300
Tell her the truth.

05:20.300 --> 05:22.733
I will speak with
the shopkeepers and see

05:22.733 --> 05:24.933
if there is anything to be done
about the ball.

05:26.633 --> 05:30.300
♪ ♪

05:30.300 --> 05:33.333
(exhales)

05:33.333 --> 05:38.500
(birds twittering)

05:43.866 --> 05:47.533
♪ ♪

05:47.533 --> 05:50.766
(horse approaching at trot)

05:56.600 --> 06:03.033
(playing notes repeatedly)

06:03.033 --> 06:04.800
Miss Markham.

06:04.800 --> 06:07.466
What cheerful tune is this?

06:07.466 --> 06:09.033
No, you're quite right.

06:09.033 --> 06:10.533
I'll stop.

06:10.533 --> 06:13.833
And take pause to apprehend
all the wonderful

06:13.833 --> 06:15.133
other diversions ahead,

06:15.133 --> 06:16.700
on what I'm sure will be

06:16.700 --> 06:18.266
an exquisite day.

06:18.266 --> 06:19.666
(slams keys loudly)

06:23.233 --> 06:25.400
Whatever's the matter?
(door slams)

06:25.400 --> 06:26.666
The ball.

06:26.666 --> 06:28.666
She believes the garden party
thwarted any chances

06:28.666 --> 06:29.666
of Mr. Colbourne

06:29.666 --> 06:30.666
letting her attend.

06:30.666 --> 06:32.433
Well, naturally.

06:32.433 --> 06:34.733
For a man of
Mr. Colbourne's disposition,

06:34.733 --> 06:36.300
to be surrounded by
happy company,

06:36.300 --> 06:38.666
enjoying lively conversation,
I think nothing could be

06:38.666 --> 06:39.733
more disagreeable.

06:39.733 --> 06:41.466
Mind your tone, please,
Miss Heywood.

06:41.466 --> 06:44.566
Mr. Colbourne doesn't deserve to
be spoken of with such contempt.

06:44.566 --> 06:46.733
Forgive me.

06:46.733 --> 06:49.333
But the man I have seen...
And how long
have you known him?

06:49.333 --> 06:51.000
There is more to
Alexander Colbourne

06:51.000 --> 06:54.233
than you can possibly imagine!

06:54.233 --> 06:57.300
♪ ♪

07:01.100 --> 07:02.166
(sighs)

07:02.166 --> 07:05.500
Who knew weddings could be
so extortionate?

07:05.500 --> 07:07.100
It's a good thing there won't be
any flowers.

07:07.100 --> 07:08.633
(door opens)

07:08.633 --> 07:10.600
Or guests.

07:10.600 --> 07:12.666
Esther!

07:12.666 --> 07:14.866
You look
uncommonly pale.

07:14.866 --> 07:17.533
I must confess
my thoughts are wayward.

07:17.533 --> 07:19.466
(warmly):
I cannot explain it.

07:19.466 --> 07:20.666
(George cooing)

07:20.666 --> 07:22.733
Has the post come yet
this morning?

07:22.733 --> 07:25.133
LADY DENHAM:
There's still nothing for you,
I'm afraid.

07:25.133 --> 07:28.266
Perhaps Babington simply
ran out of things to say.

07:28.266 --> 07:31.133
It happens
in every marriage.

07:31.133 --> 07:33.200
EDWARD:
Oh, I'm sure it's not that,
Aunt!

07:33.200 --> 07:34.933
Doubtless, Lord Babington

07:34.933 --> 07:37.100
is preoccupied
with his business affairs.

07:37.100 --> 07:39.033
I cannot believe
it's anything more than that.

07:39.033 --> 07:41.933
It's highly unlikely he would
have been led astray.

07:41.933 --> 07:43.733
He's not you, Edward!

07:45.600 --> 07:46.600
There'll be a good reason

07:46.600 --> 07:47.900
for his silence.

07:47.900 --> 07:51.766
Of course
there will.

07:51.766 --> 07:55.400
♪ ♪

07:58.333 --> 08:00.533
(George cooing)

08:00.533 --> 08:03.766
(exhales)

08:03.766 --> 08:07.900
(man shouting orders
in distance)

08:07.900 --> 08:10.366
News of Miss Heywood.

08:10.366 --> 08:12.166
They say she has plans
to return home.

08:12.166 --> 08:15.000
Tomorrow.

08:15.000 --> 08:18.100
I knew it was lost.

08:18.100 --> 08:20.000
I'm quite sunk in her esteem,
Fraser.

08:20.000 --> 08:21.500
Deservedly so.

08:21.500 --> 08:23.366
But she should have
an explanation.

08:23.366 --> 08:26.066
Nothing would come of it.

08:26.066 --> 08:29.166
(sighs):
I have acted so foolishly.

08:29.166 --> 08:31.566
And now your cowardice
compounds the ill.

08:31.566 --> 08:33.733
Seek her out.

08:33.733 --> 08:34.666
Explain yourself.

08:34.666 --> 08:36.700
Why should she end
her summer

08:36.700 --> 08:38.533
on account of your fictions?

08:38.533 --> 08:43.000
Consider her contentment, Will,
not your own glib suit.

08:43.000 --> 08:46.500
Do you really think she wants to
end her summer in Willingden?

08:46.500 --> 08:47.433
Where?

08:47.433 --> 08:49.700
The village
where she is from.

08:49.700 --> 08:51.266
Is it?

08:51.266 --> 08:52.666
Oh.

08:52.666 --> 08:56.300
A frank apology
is the remedy that she needs.

08:56.300 --> 08:57.633
That honor demands.

08:57.633 --> 09:00.333
William!

09:00.333 --> 09:03.166
Reconcile yourself
to her departure.

09:03.166 --> 09:05.300
I must.

09:11.766 --> 09:14.033
(bird squawking)

09:14.033 --> 09:16.633
Augusta said Father left
Lady Denham's in a fury.

09:16.633 --> 09:18.500
But she wouldn't say why.

09:18.500 --> 09:21.600
CHARLOTTE:
I cannot claim to know
your father's mind, Leo.

09:21.600 --> 09:24.300
Now concentrate.

09:24.300 --> 09:27.866
My elder son is
Richard the Lionheart.

09:27.866 --> 09:29.666
My younger is the king
who signed the Magna Carta.

09:29.666 --> 09:31.100
Oh, far too easy.

09:31.100 --> 09:33.700
You're Eleanor of Aquitaine.

09:33.700 --> 09:37.166
So how many soldiers
will you dance with tonight?

09:37.166 --> 09:38.266
(footsteps approaching)
(softly):
You're tiring me

09:38.266 --> 09:40.300
with all these questions.

09:40.300 --> 09:43.000
Sir.

09:43.000 --> 09:45.033
Leonora, will you leave us?

09:51.366 --> 09:53.400
Miss Heywood.

09:53.400 --> 09:55.966
I don't believe we've exchanged
a word since...

09:55.966 --> 09:57.733
Lady Denham's.

09:57.733 --> 10:00.233
Yes.

10:00.233 --> 10:02.633
I wanted to say
that I regret

10:02.633 --> 10:04.100
the way that we parted.

10:04.100 --> 10:07.966
I didn't mean
to cause offense.

10:09.400 --> 10:11.000
You wish to apologize.

10:11.000 --> 10:12.866
I cannot.

10:12.866 --> 10:15.800
♪ ♪

10:15.800 --> 10:17.900
Or explain.
Explain what?

10:19.166 --> 10:21.133
Your behavior at the
garden party.

10:21.133 --> 10:24.333
♪ ♪

10:25.600 --> 10:27.000
You have not one word to say?

10:27.000 --> 10:29.033
You have no right to demand one.

10:30.933 --> 10:33.666
Just stay away from that man.

10:33.666 --> 10:38.933
♪ ♪

10:43.333 --> 10:45.366
MARY:
I am sorry to leave you,
Alison,

10:45.366 --> 10:47.666
but Lady Denham expects me
for whist.

10:47.666 --> 10:50.033
Unless I can persuade you
to join us.

10:50.033 --> 10:51.133
Thank you, Mary,

10:51.133 --> 10:53.000
but I'd be poor company
in my current state.

10:56.800 --> 10:59.566
Mary, I, I wondered if we might
have a quick word?

10:59.566 --> 11:00.700
Not right now, my dear.

11:00.700 --> 11:02.100
Can it wait?

11:02.100 --> 11:05.300
Yes, yes, I suppose so.

11:07.433 --> 11:10.200
Alison, a scarlet coat.
(doorbell ringing)

11:11.333 --> 11:12.900
Tell him I cannot see him.
(door opens)

11:12.900 --> 11:15.300
(door closes)

11:15.300 --> 11:19.466
♪ ♪

11:22.700 --> 11:24.133
(chuckles)

11:24.133 --> 11:25.900
It's only you.

11:25.900 --> 11:27.866
♪ ♪

11:27.866 --> 11:32.933
(birds twittering)

11:40.433 --> 11:41.933
Mrs. Wheatley tells me
you're disappointed

11:41.933 --> 11:43.666
not to be going to the ball.

11:45.700 --> 11:49.866
I never harbored
much hope that I would.

11:49.866 --> 11:53.200
But it is just another reminder
of what I have lost.

11:53.200 --> 11:55.800
How do you mean?

11:55.800 --> 11:57.766
When I was a child,

11:57.766 --> 12:00.133
I used to watch my mother
get dressed to go out

12:00.133 --> 12:02.233
in the evenings.

12:02.233 --> 12:05.000
A feather in her hair.

12:05.000 --> 12:07.000
Her pearl drop earrings.

12:07.000 --> 12:09.433
Her white gloves.

12:09.433 --> 12:12.166
Sometimes she'd let me
try them on.
(laughs)

12:12.166 --> 12:17.600
And I would dance with my
father, standing on his feet.

12:17.600 --> 12:21.033
We'd talk about when I'd be old
enough to join them.

12:22.333 --> 12:25.766
Nothing can replace them.

12:25.766 --> 12:28.733
But you will dance at
plenty of balls yet.

12:28.733 --> 12:30.900
How?
(sniffles)

12:30.900 --> 12:32.633
I don't know why
you are bothering to ready me

12:32.633 --> 12:35.033
for society since I have
an uncle who is so

12:35.033 --> 12:36.833
determined to avoid it.

12:36.833 --> 12:39.033
He took you to the garden party.

12:39.033 --> 12:41.933
The only thing that
the garden party proved

12:41.933 --> 12:45.433
is that my uncle is incapable
of change.

12:45.433 --> 12:49.100
♪ ♪

12:49.100 --> 12:50.433
ALISON (voiceover):
He sends you here

12:50.433 --> 12:52.233
to argue
for his good name.

12:52.233 --> 12:55.400
I came without his knowledge.

12:55.400 --> 12:58.533
Then let us speak no more
of Captain Carter.

12:58.533 --> 13:03.266
He cannot be the only reason
for you to be here.

13:03.266 --> 13:05.200
What about your sister?
Miss Lambe?

13:06.266 --> 13:07.433
There might even be others

13:07.433 --> 13:10.333
willing to call themselves
your friend.

13:10.333 --> 13:12.800
I don't think so.

13:12.800 --> 13:14.233
A friend would oblige me
with the truth,

13:14.233 --> 13:17.000
not enjoy secret laughter
at my expense.

13:17.000 --> 13:20.900
My counsel to Captain Carter
was to tell you the truth.

13:20.900 --> 13:24.633
I couldn't betray
his confidence.

13:24.633 --> 13:28.200
How foolish am I?

13:28.200 --> 13:30.600
To give him the slightest merit
of his invented stories

13:30.600 --> 13:32.633
of the battlefield?

13:32.633 --> 13:34.500
They were not invented.

13:34.500 --> 13:35.966
Merely borrowed.

13:35.966 --> 13:38.333
From you?

13:38.333 --> 13:39.966
What does it matter now?

13:39.966 --> 13:41.700
The damage is done.

13:41.700 --> 13:44.633
Anyway, Miss Heywood,

13:44.633 --> 13:48.933
I hope you will forgive me
for my part in the deceit.

13:49.900 --> 13:51.900
It would be rather
churlish of me not to,

13:51.900 --> 13:54.100
since you did save me
from drowning.

13:54.100 --> 13:57.300
And as you say, my departure
is not on your account,

13:57.300 --> 14:00.400
so do not reproach yourself.

14:00.400 --> 14:04.600
♪ ♪

14:07.300 --> 14:10.866
BEATRICE (voiceover):
I do hope the sitting
won't last too long.

14:10.866 --> 14:13.233
With my brother conducting
a funeral in Bridport today,

14:13.233 --> 14:15.200
I shall struggle to make
his parish rounds

14:15.200 --> 14:17.200
and meet all my errands.

14:17.200 --> 14:21.666
Perhaps I shall just have to
forgo my darning circle.

14:21.666 --> 14:23.166
Thank you.

14:23.166 --> 14:24.300
Arthur!

14:24.300 --> 14:27.100
Ah...
The very person.

14:27.100 --> 14:29.233
We are due at
Mr. Lockhart's studio,

14:29.233 --> 14:31.300
but poor Miss Hankins
is rushed off her feet.

14:31.300 --> 14:34.666
I don't suppose you would
mind... chaperoning me?

14:34.666 --> 14:38.166
Alas, I have an important
meeting in an hour.

14:38.166 --> 14:39.333
That would be time enough.

14:39.333 --> 14:42.266
I know Mr. Lockhart would be
delighted to see you.

14:43.133 --> 14:44.266
Well...

14:46.000 --> 14:48.166
I suppose I could spare...

14:48.166 --> 14:50.933
(chuckling):
...a little time.

14:50.933 --> 14:56.200
(people calling and talking
in background)

14:59.633 --> 15:02.666
COLBOURNE:
Miss Heywood.

15:04.033 --> 15:06.300
On reflection,

15:06.300 --> 15:08.566
the garden party,
how I spoke to you,

15:08.566 --> 15:10.433
I cannot regret

15:10.433 --> 15:11.566
the intention of my words,

15:11.566 --> 15:14.500
but I regret the way
I expressed them.

15:15.433 --> 15:16.933
(chuckling):
Is that an apology?

15:16.933 --> 15:18.933
I believe so, yes.

15:18.933 --> 15:22.066
Then I accept it.

15:22.066 --> 15:24.366
Even if I still
do not understand.

15:28.300 --> 15:32.200
(chair scrapes floor,
seat creaks)

15:32.200 --> 15:34.666
I wished to speak to you
on Miss Markham's behalf.

15:34.666 --> 15:36.900
Oh?

15:36.900 --> 15:41.100
Mr. Colbourne, every person
contends with their past.

15:41.100 --> 15:45.600
But is it fair for yours to
constrain Miss Markham's life?

15:45.600 --> 15:47.000
And Miss Colbourne's?

15:47.000 --> 15:50.100
There is a ball tonight,
which Augusta longs to attend,

15:50.100 --> 15:51.133
but knows she will not.

15:51.133 --> 15:54.500
How am I to ready her
for society

15:54.500 --> 15:56.700
when her guardian keeps her
so confined?

15:56.700 --> 15:59.666
It renders my position
untenable.

15:59.666 --> 16:03.333
♪ ♪

16:03.333 --> 16:08.233
Then it seems you have
some thinking ahead of you.

16:08.233 --> 16:12.100
You will inform me
once you've made a decision.

16:12.100 --> 16:14.000
(papers rustling)

16:14.000 --> 16:18.766
♪ ♪

16:18.766 --> 16:20.933
(door closes)

16:23.300 --> 16:25.700
(birds twittering)

16:32.166 --> 16:34.333
(gasps):
Oh, gracious.

16:34.333 --> 16:38.066
I fear we must be leaving,
Miss Lambe, or I shall be late.

16:38.066 --> 16:42.266
Could you not just
leave us to it, Arthur?

16:42.266 --> 16:43.966
And return after
your meeting?

16:43.966 --> 16:46.633
Oh, Mary would not approve of
my leaving you unchaperoned.

16:46.633 --> 16:48.600
Or Miss Hankins,
for that matter.

16:48.600 --> 16:50.600
There is a certain...

16:50.600 --> 16:52.566
...alchemy that occurs

16:52.566 --> 16:55.200
when a painter and a sitter

16:55.200 --> 16:57.500
are alone.

16:58.466 --> 17:01.866
As someone with
such a feeling for art,

17:01.866 --> 17:04.366
surely you can understand that?

17:04.366 --> 17:09.333
♪ ♪

17:12.166 --> 17:14.366
MARY:
My congratulations,
Miss Brereton.

17:14.366 --> 17:16.633
Have you decided where
you and Captain Denham

17:16.633 --> 17:19.233
will live
once you're married?
Not yet.

17:19.233 --> 17:22.233
LADY DENHAM:
I suppose that rather depends on
where Edward's company

17:22.233 --> 17:24.100
flits to next.

17:24.100 --> 17:26.366
"Flit," milady?

17:26.366 --> 17:28.866
Well, it seems our Colonel
Lennox has quite a reputation.

17:28.866 --> 17:31.166
I've just heard from a friend
in Ramsgate.

17:31.166 --> 17:34.900
Evidently, when the company
were stationed there last year,

17:34.900 --> 17:37.266
they drank the town dry,

17:37.266 --> 17:39.033
ran up debts with
every tradesman,

17:39.033 --> 17:42.100
and then vanished overnight.

17:42.100 --> 17:44.166
Surely they cannot just
outrun their debts?

17:44.166 --> 17:45.500
Oh, on the contrary.

17:45.500 --> 17:47.700
These men are war heroes.

17:47.700 --> 17:51.000
The shopkeepers looked for
legal recourse quite in vain.

17:51.000 --> 17:54.566
And it seems that Ramsgate
is not the only town

17:54.566 --> 17:56.266
to suffer such a fate.

17:56.266 --> 17:59.200
So, you might wish
to communicate this

17:59.200 --> 18:01.733
to Mr. Parker.

18:01.733 --> 18:04.166
Forewarned is fore-armed.

18:10.666 --> 18:16.133
♪ ♪

18:17.866 --> 18:20.866
(slurring):
I am the winner, am I not?

18:22.766 --> 18:23.800
CLARA:
No, Esther.

18:23.800 --> 18:26.033
We are on the same team.

18:26.033 --> 18:31.800
♪ ♪

18:31.800 --> 18:35.633
Excuse me.

18:35.633 --> 18:39.600
I'm very tired all of a sudden.

18:39.600 --> 18:43.666
♪ ♪

18:47.000 --> 18:52.966
(birds twittering)

18:58.500 --> 19:01.066
You changed your hair.

19:01.066 --> 19:02.100
You asked me

19:02.100 --> 19:04.966
how I wished to be seen.

19:04.966 --> 19:06.766
This is the hair my mother
gave me.

19:08.366 --> 19:11.566
What did your father give you?

19:11.566 --> 19:13.800
Education.

19:13.800 --> 19:15.433
An inheritance.

19:15.433 --> 19:18.433
Which is both a blessing
and a curse.

19:18.433 --> 19:21.066
Had I your inheritance,

19:21.066 --> 19:23.833
I would travel the world.

19:23.833 --> 19:26.933
I would do nothing but eat,

19:26.933 --> 19:30.300
drink, paint...

19:30.300 --> 19:33.500
Swim.

19:33.500 --> 19:36.733
And then I would spend
the rest of my time...

19:40.866 --> 19:43.100
(softly):
...in bed.

19:47.833 --> 19:49.200
And then I wouldn't have
to do

19:49.200 --> 19:51.333
another miserable commission.
(chuckles)

19:54.633 --> 19:57.933
I'm sorry this is
such an ordeal.

19:59.133 --> 20:02.133
Not you, Miss Lambe.

20:02.133 --> 20:05.033
You must have realized
that I'm not,

20:05.033 --> 20:08.433
not doing this for money.

20:10.266 --> 20:12.966
But for love.

20:12.966 --> 20:19.066
♪ ♪

20:32.033 --> 20:37.200
♪ ♪

20:39.033 --> 20:41.066
MARY:
Lady Denham said

20:41.066 --> 20:42.666
she heard it from a friend.

20:42.666 --> 20:44.366
Apparently, Colonel Lennox
and his men

20:44.366 --> 20:46.266
simply vanished overnight,

20:46.266 --> 20:48.166
leaving all their bills unpaid.

20:48.166 --> 20:49.566
Overnight?

20:49.566 --> 20:51.966
And it seems the law
cannot touch them.

20:51.966 --> 20:53.166
That is all the more reason why,

20:53.166 --> 20:55.700
for the sake of the town,
we must resolve this now

20:55.700 --> 20:56.866
before they disappear.

20:56.866 --> 20:59.266
Mary.

20:59.266 --> 21:01.600
There is something else
I must tell you.

21:04.033 --> 21:05.933
Something I've been
keeping from you.

21:09.933 --> 21:11.666
Tom?

21:11.666 --> 21:14.900
Colonel Lennox will not
repay the shopkeepers' debts

21:14.900 --> 21:16.033
until I've repaid my own.

21:16.033 --> 21:18.466
What debts?
A dice game.

21:18.466 --> 21:21.700
He deliberately trapped me,
Mary.

21:23.233 --> 21:26.433
How much?

21:26.433 --> 21:29.600
A hundred pounds.

21:31.466 --> 21:32.700
Have you learnt nothing?

21:32.700 --> 21:35.133
I am so sorry.

21:35.133 --> 21:38.466
After everything
we endured last year!

21:38.466 --> 21:40.866
Everything that Sidney
sacrificed!

21:42.800 --> 21:44.100
What do you mean,
"sacrificed"?

21:45.666 --> 21:49.800
Did you really never
work it out?

21:49.800 --> 21:53.766
Sidney and Charlotte
were in love.

21:53.766 --> 21:56.133
He married Eliza to save you.

21:56.133 --> 21:58.466
But you would throw

21:58.466 --> 22:02.400
all that away
for a game of dice!

22:04.100 --> 22:05.166
(door closes)

22:05.166 --> 22:10.966
♪ ♪

22:17.133 --> 22:19.566
♪ ♪

22:19.566 --> 22:23.466
(weakly):
What do you want, Edward?
(door closes)

22:25.400 --> 22:28.500
I know I'm the last person
you would seek comfort from now.

22:28.500 --> 22:31.833
But I know you
better than anyone.

22:31.833 --> 22:35.766
And it frightens me
to see you like this.

22:35.766 --> 22:38.466
I'm just a little dizzy,
that's all.

22:40.333 --> 22:44.400
You cannot see
how you appear.

22:44.400 --> 22:46.833
I fear you're in the grip

22:46.833 --> 22:48.300
of some kind of mania.

22:50.666 --> 22:53.233
Why is this happening to me,
Edward?

22:53.233 --> 22:58.466
♪ ♪

23:01.233 --> 23:02.366
Sleep now.

23:05.166 --> 23:08.200
You will feel
much the better for it.

23:12.600 --> 23:17.100
♪ ♪

23:28.766 --> 23:32.833
(seagull squawking)

23:32.833 --> 23:37.066
(soldiers laughing, chatting)

23:40.033 --> 23:45.200
♪ ♪

23:56.466 --> 23:59.666
It's you making her ill.

23:59.666 --> 24:02.666
In London, I saw unfortunates
with matching symptoms:

24:02.666 --> 24:03.933
scratching...

24:03.933 --> 24:05.366
(softly):
Laudanum!

24:05.366 --> 24:07.000
You've exchanged it
for her concoction!

24:07.000 --> 24:09.166
Don't feign shock, Clara--
you agreed to this.

24:09.166 --> 24:12.133
I didn't agree to poison her.

24:12.133 --> 24:14.566
Then why tell me
she was taking it?

24:14.566 --> 24:16.233
Besides, it's working--
she's unraveling.

24:16.233 --> 24:17.633
The moment Lady Denham
believes her mad,

24:17.633 --> 24:19.400
she will rapidly
disinherit her.

24:19.400 --> 24:22.200
She takes that tincture
because she wants a child.

24:22.200 --> 24:24.066
This seems especially cruel,
Edward,

24:24.066 --> 24:25.166
even for you.

24:25.166 --> 24:28.333
And it gladdens me
that she cannot have one.

24:28.333 --> 24:32.066
And if Babington believes
her mad, so much the better.

24:32.066 --> 24:35.766
This is not just about George.

24:35.766 --> 24:37.400
This is revenge.

24:37.400 --> 24:38.800
She betrayed my trust,

24:38.800 --> 24:41.900
and for that there are
consequences.

24:41.900 --> 24:45.766
(grabs Clara's arm):
She shall attend
the ball tonight.

24:45.766 --> 24:49.133
Make sure of it.

24:49.133 --> 24:50.266
(releases arm)

24:52.300 --> 24:53.700
(exhales)

24:53.700 --> 24:56.400
(dog barking in distance)

24:59.166 --> 25:01.133
ARTHUR:
Ah, there you are!

25:01.133 --> 25:03.566
You must get changed, or we'll
be late to our own ball.

25:03.566 --> 25:05.733
It is going ahead?

25:05.733 --> 25:07.266
But how?

25:07.266 --> 25:09.366
As luck would have it,
I was, until recently,

25:09.366 --> 25:12.166
a loyal customer of
Mr. Chorston's bakery.

25:12.166 --> 25:14.766
Chorston won the others
round.

25:14.766 --> 25:16.166
They agreed to an extra

25:16.166 --> 25:17.733
three days' credit.

25:17.733 --> 25:19.366
You are a marvel,
Arthur!

25:19.366 --> 25:21.533
A marvel!

25:23.600 --> 25:26.000
There's something different
about you tonight.

25:26.000 --> 25:28.366
A new brightness
in your eyes.

25:28.366 --> 25:31.433
I wonder, how is that
portrait progressing?

25:31.433 --> 25:34.833
Faster than I had expected.

25:34.833 --> 25:39.466
Mr. Lockhart is
prodigiously talented.

25:39.466 --> 25:42.733
How did you fare with
Mr. Colbourne today?

25:42.733 --> 25:43.833
(sighs)

25:43.833 --> 25:45.633
I fear everyone's
judgment was sound.

25:45.633 --> 25:47.733
About him

25:47.733 --> 25:49.333
and the imprudence
of my ambition.

25:49.333 --> 25:50.600
(sighs)

25:50.600 --> 25:53.100
But what will you do if
you're no longer a governess?

25:54.233 --> 25:55.366
I don't know.

25:55.366 --> 25:56.900
You're not going to return
to Willingden

25:56.900 --> 25:57.900
and marry that farmer.

25:57.900 --> 25:59.100
Ralph?!

25:59.100 --> 26:00.566
No.

26:00.566 --> 26:04.333
I don't understand why you won't
consider Colonel Lennox.

26:04.333 --> 26:05.400
He's handsome.

26:05.400 --> 26:06.400
Noble.

26:06.400 --> 26:07.400
You enjoy each other's company.

26:07.400 --> 26:08.600
Georgiana...

26:08.600 --> 26:13.800
You can't recapture
what you had with Sidney.

26:13.800 --> 26:17.966
I will never love anyone
as I loved Otis.

26:17.966 --> 26:21.833
That doesn't mean I can't find
different kinds of passion.

26:21.833 --> 26:24.600
♪ ♪

26:24.600 --> 26:25.666
ALISON:
Charlotte?

26:25.666 --> 26:27.766
GEORGIANA:
Alison!

26:27.766 --> 26:29.933
I have not seen
that gown before.

26:29.933 --> 26:32.766
It is my May Day dress,
from home.

26:33.833 --> 26:35.700
What convinced you
to come?

26:35.700 --> 26:37.000
His shame, not mine.

26:37.000 --> 26:38.833
Why should I hide away?

26:38.833 --> 26:41.000
Well, then,
your liveliest spirits.

26:41.000 --> 26:42.133
And Charlotte,

26:42.133 --> 26:44.166
as this is our last night
as a happy trio,

26:44.166 --> 26:46.000
you must promise
to enjoy yourself.

26:46.000 --> 26:47.733
Fine, yes,
I promise.

26:47.733 --> 26:49.400
I think this means she
will dance with the colonel.

26:49.400 --> 26:50.666
I did not say that.

26:50.666 --> 26:54.333
No, but when you're wrapped
in his strong arms,

26:54.333 --> 26:55.900
I shall be
studying you closely.

26:55.900 --> 26:59.100
I somehow doubt you'll
maintain your present composure.

26:59.100 --> 27:00.733
Oh, you're both
impossible.

27:00.733 --> 27:03.200
(laughing)

27:03.200 --> 27:09.100
♪ ♪

27:12.666 --> 27:14.066
Hm.

27:15.600 --> 27:18.366
Wish me luck, Fraser.

27:18.366 --> 27:20.600
With what, sir?

27:20.600 --> 27:22.500
Let's just say I hope I receive

27:22.500 --> 27:24.100
a better response
from my Miss Heywood

27:24.100 --> 27:27.000
than Captain Carter
did from his.

27:32.300 --> 27:33.866
Whoa!

27:35.433 --> 27:37.066
(horse nickering)

27:37.066 --> 27:38.666
(laughing)

27:40.000 --> 27:41.133
(carriage door closes)

27:41.133 --> 27:43.700
(gasps, laughs)

27:43.700 --> 27:48.900
♪ ♪

27:48.900 --> 27:53.866
(people talking in background)

27:53.866 --> 27:57.033
(quietly):
Was this wise?

28:02.366 --> 28:06.266
♪ ♪

28:09.433 --> 28:11.266
GEORGIANA:
Mary tells me there will be

28:11.266 --> 28:13.600
some highly eligible
gentlemen here.

28:13.600 --> 28:15.566
Quite so, Georgiana.

28:15.566 --> 28:17.866
Yes, we shall see you married
by your 21st birthday yet.

28:20.000 --> 28:23.200
And, and you, Charlotte.

28:23.200 --> 28:25.833
I hope that you will
be dancing this evening.

28:25.833 --> 28:27.666
I, I know that Sidney

28:27.666 --> 28:31.700
would want to see you
dancing again.

28:32.633 --> 28:34.766
As do I.

28:37.066 --> 28:38.033
Thank you, Tom.

28:38.033 --> 28:39.800
Yes.

28:43.400 --> 28:45.200
Ah, Lady Denham.

28:48.566 --> 28:50.066
Of course, you know my
betrothed, Miss Brereton.

28:50.066 --> 28:53.400
Oh, herzlichen Glückwunsch
to you both.

28:54.933 --> 28:56.333
How proud you must be, milady!

28:56.333 --> 28:58.833
Oh, you can
hardly imagine!

28:58.833 --> 29:00.933
FUCHS:
And Lady Babington,

29:00.933 --> 29:03.066
I hope you are well.

29:03.066 --> 29:05.200
So do I.

29:08.500 --> 29:12.166
♪ ♪

29:15.266 --> 29:17.233
Good luck,
Colonel.

29:18.200 --> 29:19.966
Miss Heywood,

29:19.966 --> 29:22.800
permit me
the honor of the first dance.

29:22.800 --> 29:24.100
She would be delighted.

29:30.366 --> 29:32.700
(song begins)

29:41.400 --> 29:45.800
(song continues)

29:45.800 --> 29:47.700
It doesn't seem so long ago

29:47.700 --> 29:49.200
since the first time
we danced together.

29:49.200 --> 29:52.966
To think how much has
happened since that night.

29:55.200 --> 29:57.933
Is it not remarkable
how the path of one's life

29:57.933 --> 30:00.866
can be so altered
in just a few short weeks?

30:05.866 --> 30:07.366
No doubt
Mrs. Parker has told you

30:07.366 --> 30:09.800
that the Army, it seems,
will be gone

30:09.800 --> 30:12.066
in a puff of smoke.

30:12.066 --> 30:16.066
You insisted that they would
benefit Sanditon financially,

30:16.066 --> 30:18.333
but it seems
the opposite is true.

30:18.333 --> 30:19.900
I did warn you.

30:19.900 --> 30:22.300
I, I do not in fact
recall any warnings.

30:22.300 --> 30:23.633
What do you intend
to do about it?

30:23.633 --> 30:27.600
You endorsed these
scarlet-coated rogues

30:27.600 --> 30:29.766
in the strongest
possible terms.

30:29.766 --> 30:32.566
I entrusted you with my money,
as did your brother's widow.

30:32.566 --> 30:34.633
Well, maybe that trust
was misplaced.

30:34.633 --> 30:38.166
Oh, in heaven's name,
what's wrong with you?

30:38.166 --> 30:40.100
Find a remedy.

30:40.100 --> 30:42.833
(song continues)

30:42.833 --> 30:44.466
Tom?

30:53.166 --> 30:55.266
It's most agreeable
to enjoy your company

30:55.266 --> 30:57.566
without fear of interruption
by your employer.

30:57.566 --> 30:59.266
Quite.

30:59.266 --> 31:00.933
Although I cannot say
with certainty

31:00.933 --> 31:02.400
how long he shall remain
my employer.

31:03.500 --> 31:04.900
I am glad to hear it.

31:09.300 --> 31:11.633
Does that suggest you have been
giving some thought

31:11.633 --> 31:13.000
to your future,

31:13.000 --> 31:14.166
Miss Heywood?

31:14.166 --> 31:17.366
(song ends, crowd applauds)

31:17.366 --> 31:19.066
Excuse me, Colonel.

31:19.066 --> 31:21.266
My sister needs me.

31:22.966 --> 31:24.633
(applause fades)

31:28.066 --> 31:29.533
(new song begins)

31:31.033 --> 31:34.100
(people laughing)

31:34.100 --> 31:35.966
I think I preferred
the main room.

31:35.966 --> 31:37.266
Yes, shall we?

31:37.266 --> 31:38.733
No.

31:38.733 --> 31:40.433
For my own pride,
I cannot let this stand.

31:40.433 --> 31:42.066
(laughing)

31:47.100 --> 31:48.233
Miss Heywood.

31:48.233 --> 31:51.766
I was sorry to hear
you were leaving Sanditon.

31:51.766 --> 31:53.400
I am hardly inclined
to believe you,

31:53.400 --> 31:55.333
since you have made no attempt
to explain your actions.

31:55.333 --> 31:56.266
No, you are right.

31:56.266 --> 31:57.866
I, um...
It fell to Captain Fraser

31:57.866 --> 31:59.500
to beg forgiveness
in your place.

31:59.500 --> 32:01.433
It was he that asked me to stay

32:01.433 --> 32:03.400
because he is a man of honor
and integrity.

32:03.400 --> 32:06.533
Believe me, it was only
self-reproach that prevented me.

32:06.533 --> 32:08.900
Let us put
this discord behind us.

32:08.900 --> 32:11.533
I beg you, do me the honor
of this next dance.

32:11.533 --> 32:14.733
I will not dance with you.

32:14.733 --> 32:16.733
I came only to say

32:16.733 --> 32:19.433
I was fool enough
to indulge your falsehoods,

32:19.433 --> 32:21.866
but please consider
your behavior.

32:21.866 --> 32:25.500
Perhaps you may
spare the next girl.

32:33.033 --> 32:37.066
(people talking and laughing
in background)

32:37.066 --> 32:38.533
ESTHER:
Oh, to watch you two
parade around

32:38.533 --> 32:40.666
like a parody of devotion,
it's grotesque.

32:40.666 --> 32:42.666
I can't believe you sanctioned
this sham of a wedding, Aunt.

32:42.666 --> 32:45.966
It's called making
the best of a bad situation.

32:45.966 --> 32:48.433
I'm sorry you can't
be happy for us, Esther.

32:48.433 --> 32:50.833
Don't let your own
marital discord mar our joy.

32:50.833 --> 32:52.066
Joy?

32:52.066 --> 32:53.400
Clara is your captive.

32:53.400 --> 32:54.700
She bears you
no more love than I do.

32:56.666 --> 32:59.200
Here, take this.
(glass shatters)

32:59.200 --> 33:01.566
(sighs)
Are you quite all right?

33:01.566 --> 33:02.933
Yes, I didn't...

33:02.933 --> 33:05.200
Esther, what's got
into you?

33:05.200 --> 33:07.533
Perhaps we should have
left you behind.

33:07.533 --> 33:08.433
Here, take mine.

33:08.433 --> 33:11.066
(sighs)

33:11.066 --> 33:12.966
(Esther exhales sharply)

33:12.966 --> 33:16.533
♪ ♪

33:16.533 --> 33:18.966
Something preys on my mind,
Aunt.

33:18.966 --> 33:20.266
Esther told me once,
on her paternal line,

33:20.266 --> 33:23.033
her grandfather once
lived 30 years in a madhouse.

33:23.033 --> 33:25.300
Oh, nonsense.

33:25.300 --> 33:26.866
Esther's not mad.

33:26.866 --> 33:30.033
She's just confused,
that's all.

33:30.033 --> 33:32.800
What is wrong with me?

33:32.800 --> 33:35.333
If Babington returns
to find me like this...

33:35.333 --> 33:36.400
(exhales)

33:36.400 --> 33:37.366
If he returns.

33:37.366 --> 33:39.633
He will.
(sighs)

33:39.633 --> 33:43.466
♪ ♪

33:53.300 --> 33:56.166
Miss Lambe, I trust you are
having a pleasant evening.

33:58.733 --> 34:00.600
Mr. Lockhart.

34:00.600 --> 34:02.866
Passably so, thank you.

34:02.866 --> 34:05.200
I know I'm only
a humble artist,

34:05.200 --> 34:09.166
but would it be a presumption
if I were to ask you to dance?

34:09.166 --> 34:11.966
I hardly think
my guardians would approve.

34:11.966 --> 34:15.266
Oh, come now.

34:15.266 --> 34:17.066
It's only dancing.

34:19.166 --> 34:21.033
Where is the harm?

34:21.033 --> 34:25.133
(energetic song begins)

34:27.233 --> 34:29.466
(partygoers whooping)

34:35.900 --> 34:41.666
(song continues)

34:47.266 --> 34:49.700
You know Mr. Lockhart
better than I do, Arthur.

34:49.700 --> 34:52.233
Can we trust him
with Georgiana?

34:52.233 --> 34:54.466
ARTHUR:
Look at how he
lights her up, Mary.

34:54.466 --> 34:57.000
I would trust him with my life.

34:57.000 --> 35:02.000
(song continues)

35:13.633 --> 35:16.200
♪ ♪

35:16.200 --> 35:17.633
(song stops)

35:17.633 --> 35:19.700
(groans)

35:19.700 --> 35:21.100
It's too much wine,
I think.

35:23.000 --> 35:26.466
♪ ♪

35:30.400 --> 35:32.733
She did very well to
interrupt us.

35:32.733 --> 35:34.300
I did not like
that dance at all.

35:34.300 --> 35:35.833
(chuckling)

35:35.833 --> 35:38.966
Something less jaunty, please.

35:38.966 --> 35:41.333
(musicians start slower piece)

35:41.333 --> 35:44.200
Come with me.

35:47.600 --> 35:49.166
I believe the cause

35:49.166 --> 35:51.433
to be Lady Babington's
unhappy condition.

35:51.433 --> 35:54.066
How?

35:54.066 --> 35:57.400
In essence, her brain is
impaired by nonsensical messages

35:57.400 --> 35:59.733
from her flawed womb.

35:59.733 --> 36:03.000
In science,
we call it hysteria.

36:03.000 --> 36:04.233
Interesting
that her symptoms began

36:04.233 --> 36:06.266
just as she started

36:06.266 --> 36:09.833
taking your
ridiculous concoctions,

36:09.833 --> 36:11.100
your "tincture."

36:11.100 --> 36:12.233
Impossible.

36:12.233 --> 36:14.133
It is a harmless placebo.

36:14.133 --> 36:16.700
It cannot affect her physically.

36:16.700 --> 36:19.100
I seek only to give her hope.

36:20.533 --> 36:23.966
Esther,
come, we must go,

36:23.966 --> 36:25.766
before you
humiliate yourself further.

36:33.900 --> 36:38.000
♪ ♪

36:38.000 --> 36:40.700
Charlotte!

36:43.133 --> 36:46.966
♪ ♪

36:54.600 --> 36:57.366
I don't know what kind of
a spell you've put on him.

37:00.233 --> 37:02.200
I'm sure it wasn't
just my words.

37:02.200 --> 37:04.400
And I'm sure it was--
you must never leave us.

37:06.833 --> 37:08.766
The next dance
is about to begin.

37:08.766 --> 37:11.133
I... (chuckles)
You know I do not dance.

37:11.133 --> 37:13.433
It is a ball, Mr. Colbourne.

37:13.433 --> 37:14.766
Why else are you here?

37:14.766 --> 37:17.766
I'm asking myself
that same question.

37:20.266 --> 37:25.000
CHARLES:
How long do you plan
to remain here in Sanditon?

37:25.000 --> 37:29.166
If it were down to me,
only until I come of age.

37:31.233 --> 37:34.366
But if the Parkers
have their way,

37:34.366 --> 37:37.433
I'll be stuck here
until I marry.

37:37.433 --> 37:39.700
How long will you stay?

37:42.566 --> 37:45.666
Until tomorrow.

37:45.666 --> 37:49.433
As soon as your portrait
is finished,

37:49.433 --> 37:50.900
I shall be leaving for Europe.

37:53.566 --> 37:55.133
Were you going to tell me?

37:56.433 --> 37:58.133
This is me telling you.

38:00.466 --> 38:03.233
So this is goodbye?

38:03.233 --> 38:05.800
It doesn't have to be.

38:11.466 --> 38:13.266
Come with me.

38:14.400 --> 38:15.833
As your concubine?

38:15.833 --> 38:19.200
(softly):
As my wife!

38:19.200 --> 38:21.333
MARY:
Georgiana! There you are!

38:21.333 --> 38:23.700
(gasps)

38:23.700 --> 38:26.466
MARY:
I thought you'd disappeared.

38:26.466 --> 38:27.866
Come along.

38:27.866 --> 38:30.000
♪ ♪

38:30.000 --> 38:33.233
(door opens, closes)

38:33.233 --> 38:36.500
(exhales sharply)

38:36.500 --> 38:41.066
(song playing)

38:54.400 --> 38:57.266
(song continues)

39:07.033 --> 39:09.433
I wonder, have you given
any more consideration

39:09.433 --> 39:10.433
to your position?

39:10.433 --> 39:13.833
CHARLOTTE:
A great deal.

39:13.833 --> 39:17.133
I hope we might
persuade you to stay.

39:17.133 --> 39:20.300
Why is that?

39:20.300 --> 39:21.800
Augusta and Leonora
have been transformed

39:21.800 --> 39:24.333
by your influence.

39:24.333 --> 39:27.000
I cannot explain the
effect you have had,

39:27.000 --> 39:29.266
Miss Heywood,
on all of us.

39:35.400 --> 39:39.633
It's as if you've restored us
back to life.

39:39.633 --> 39:42.100
We would be bereft
to lose you now.

39:42.100 --> 39:45.933
(song continues)

40:03.933 --> 40:05.933
(song ends)

40:05.933 --> 40:07.000
(crowd applauds)

40:07.000 --> 40:08.566
Excuse me.

40:15.066 --> 40:18.500
(exhales):
There you are.

40:22.566 --> 40:27.433
How could I let him
lead me into such a bind?

40:27.433 --> 40:30.933
Because that is
what he does.

40:30.933 --> 40:32.833
He is a colonel--

40:32.833 --> 40:37.166
an expert in strategy
and setting ambushes.

40:38.933 --> 40:41.833
I was casting around,
looking for someone to,

40:41.833 --> 40:43.900
to endow with all the qualities
I miss in our brother,

40:43.900 --> 40:45.533
and, and there he was.

40:45.533 --> 40:49.133
Sidney is irreplaceable.

40:50.933 --> 40:55.000
But you have a quality
that he never had.

40:55.000 --> 40:57.200
You are a man of vision.

40:57.200 --> 40:59.800
Were it not for you,
Sanditon would be

40:59.800 --> 41:02.900
little more than
a row of fishing huts.

41:02.900 --> 41:06.633
You have a rare imagination.

41:08.166 --> 41:13.833
A genius for conjuring
up ideas out of nothing.

41:16.133 --> 41:18.966
You will think
of something, Tom.

41:18.966 --> 41:22.366
You always do.

41:23.466 --> 41:25.366
What would I do without you,
Arthur?

41:26.800 --> 41:29.800
Why was I looking for someone
to fill Sidney's shoes

41:29.800 --> 41:31.233
when you, you've been
there all along?

41:31.233 --> 41:34.300
♪ ♪

41:34.300 --> 41:35.966
My brother.

41:36.866 --> 41:38.333
(sniffles)

41:43.366 --> 41:45.666
(people talking in background)

41:45.666 --> 41:46.866
Charlotte.

41:46.866 --> 41:48.633
What is the matter?

41:48.633 --> 41:50.100
I don't understand.

41:50.100 --> 41:53.366
Dancing just now, I felt alive
in a way I haven't since...

41:53.366 --> 41:55.666
You are allowed to
have feelings for another man.

41:55.666 --> 41:57.033
That is not a betrayal.

41:57.033 --> 42:00.500
But... Why him?

42:00.500 --> 42:02.833
Why not him?

42:02.833 --> 42:04.033
Speaking of whom.

42:04.033 --> 42:07.133
LENNOX:
Miss Heywood.

42:07.133 --> 42:08.400
I shall see you downstairs.

42:11.766 --> 42:15.233
I hoped we could conclude
our conversation at last.

42:17.733 --> 42:21.000
(song begins)

42:33.066 --> 42:36.433
Army life defines a man.

42:36.433 --> 42:39.400
I've never been defeated
on the field of battle,

42:39.400 --> 42:44.066
but now I fear
I am quite conquered.

42:46.266 --> 42:49.133
I have never met
anyone comparable,

42:49.133 --> 42:50.266
Miss Heywood.

42:50.266 --> 42:52.566
You surprise me
constantly.

42:52.566 --> 42:55.366
Nothing, nothing
would delight me so much as

42:55.366 --> 42:56.566
to be constant to you.

42:56.566 --> 42:58.133
I...

42:58.133 --> 42:59.200
There's a large estate
along the coast

42:59.200 --> 43:00.566
with a very pleasant
aspect.

43:00.566 --> 43:03.700
I took the liberty of
making enquiries.

43:03.700 --> 43:05.566
I do not understand.

43:05.566 --> 43:08.200
Of course you do.

43:08.200 --> 43:10.533
I believe you have understood
since our first meeting.

43:10.533 --> 43:13.533
I humbly beg of you,
give me your hand.

43:15.800 --> 43:18.200
I wish you to be my wife.

43:18.200 --> 43:19.700
♪ ♪

43:19.700 --> 43:23.100
I, I thought I'd been clear.

43:23.100 --> 43:24.633
I do not wish to marry.

43:24.633 --> 43:26.766
The time for
playing games is over.

43:26.766 --> 43:28.433
I play no game.

43:28.433 --> 43:29.633
I am perfectly serious.

43:29.633 --> 43:31.533
You worry I wouldn't suit
a domestic life.

43:31.533 --> 43:32.600
I assure you, I...

43:32.600 --> 43:34.766
I cannot marry you.

43:34.766 --> 43:37.066
You can't want to
continue as a governess.

43:37.066 --> 43:39.433
I am offering to save you
from that squalid existence.

43:39.433 --> 43:42.000
I do not love you!
Love will grow if you let it.

43:43.100 --> 43:44.833
(struggling):
Stop!

43:44.833 --> 43:46.733
Be sensible of my rank!

43:46.733 --> 43:48.333
Know your own!

43:48.333 --> 43:50.766
I know who I am.

43:50.766 --> 43:53.633
I've never pretended to be
anyone else.

43:56.333 --> 43:58.366
♪ ♪

43:58.366 --> 44:00.633
(gasping)
Miss Heywood...

44:01.633 --> 44:03.866
What is it?

44:03.866 --> 44:05.700
(Charlotte exhaling)

44:05.700 --> 44:07.133
What did he say to you?

44:07.133 --> 44:09.233
(gasping)

44:09.233 --> 44:12.900
♪ ♪

44:12.900 --> 44:14.700
(people talking,
laughing in background)

44:16.900 --> 44:19.366
Abandoned and in want
of friends again, I see.

44:19.366 --> 44:20.366
Captain Fraser.

44:20.366 --> 44:21.833
How do you always find

44:21.833 --> 44:25.166
the most perfect words
of comfort?

44:25.166 --> 44:28.800
My entire summer wasted.

44:28.800 --> 44:31.833
Tomorrow, when you're
mucking out your father's pigs,

44:31.833 --> 44:33.366
you'll have time to
consider that.

44:33.366 --> 44:36.933
Now, we're at a ball,

44:36.933 --> 44:39.166
you are wearing
the most beautiful gown here,

44:39.166 --> 44:41.666
and I must insist we dance.

44:43.000 --> 44:44.533
This dress is
the plainest in the room.

44:44.533 --> 44:45.833
You are mocking me once again.

44:45.833 --> 44:47.966
No, Miss Heywood.

44:47.966 --> 44:49.966
Simple is not plain.

44:49.966 --> 44:51.666
True beauty
needs no adornment.

44:51.666 --> 44:55.666
I say to you now
in all sincerity

44:55.666 --> 44:58.033
that you have
never looked lovelier.

44:58.933 --> 45:01.833
Thank you.

45:01.833 --> 45:03.400
That is worth all the more

45:03.400 --> 45:05.200
coming from
the rudest man I know.

45:06.100 --> 45:08.166
(chuckles)

45:10.266 --> 45:12.100
This is what
I tried to warn you of.

45:12.100 --> 45:13.900
You didn't warn me
of anything.

45:13.900 --> 45:15.533
You ordered me
to avoid him

45:15.533 --> 45:16.566
and gave no reason.

45:16.566 --> 45:17.700
My only thought
was to protect you

45:17.700 --> 45:19.333
from a man
I knew to be dangerous.

45:19.333 --> 45:20.866
Then why did you
not say?

45:20.866 --> 45:23.433
All I had was the
colonel's account.

45:23.433 --> 45:25.766
He told me that
you were not to be trusted.

45:25.766 --> 45:28.166
That...

45:28.166 --> 45:29.900
Go on.

45:31.500 --> 45:34.733
That you stole the woman he
loved and destroyed her.

45:34.733 --> 45:37.766
That is what he told you?

45:37.766 --> 45:40.133
So what is the truth?

45:40.133 --> 45:43.566
I have had enough of these
endless riddles and evasions.

45:43.566 --> 45:46.700
Of trying to find meaning
in your silences.

45:47.600 --> 45:49.333
This is not the place.

45:49.333 --> 45:51.400
I must know who you are.

45:51.400 --> 45:53.700
♪ ♪

45:53.700 --> 45:55.866
Uncle?

45:55.866 --> 45:59.366
Miss Heywood.

45:59.366 --> 46:00.566
What is it?

46:00.566 --> 46:02.533
We're leaving.

46:03.933 --> 46:07.966
Miss Heywood will
come with us.

46:07.966 --> 46:12.500
♪ ♪

46:12.500 --> 46:15.600
FRASER:
So you leave tomorrow.

46:15.600 --> 46:17.566
A bright new dawn
for Sanditon.

46:17.566 --> 46:19.166
We'll be celebrating
in the streets.

46:19.166 --> 46:22.833
How I will miss
your sense of humor.

46:22.833 --> 46:24.666
(song playing)

46:40.433 --> 46:43.866
(song continues)

46:57.100 --> 47:03.233
(song continues)

47:13.033 --> 47:14.633
(song ends)

47:14.633 --> 47:18.433
(crowd applauds)

47:20.733 --> 47:23.633
Miss Leonora
has been impossible:

47:23.633 --> 47:25.833
up and down from her
bed all evening.

47:25.833 --> 47:27.166
Miss Heywood.

47:27.166 --> 47:30.400
I was not
expecting you.

47:30.400 --> 47:32.466
Did you dance, Augusta?

47:34.800 --> 47:36.266
Miss Heywood!

47:36.266 --> 47:37.833
Come, girls,
let us leave your father

47:37.833 --> 47:39.900
and Miss Heywood in peace.

47:41.033 --> 47:42.666
(quietly):
I'll tell you
everything tomorrow.

47:42.666 --> 47:47.600
♪ ♪

47:58.133 --> 48:00.200
Hysteria, Aunt.

48:00.200 --> 48:01.933
What if she begins to rave?

48:01.933 --> 48:04.433
We may not be able to provide
care to her best advantage.

48:04.433 --> 48:06.700
We need not consider
that now.

48:06.700 --> 48:08.733
These affairs
only go one way.

48:08.733 --> 48:11.200
Well, where would she go?

48:11.200 --> 48:12.333
Where is George?

48:12.333 --> 48:13.366
Do you have him?

48:13.366 --> 48:16.500
(George crying)

48:19.566 --> 48:25.300
(Esther humming,
George breathing evenly)

48:25.300 --> 48:26.766
LADY DENHAM:
Esther!

48:26.766 --> 48:28.800
(George crying)
CLARA:
What are you doing?

48:28.800 --> 48:30.033
Don't hurt him!

48:30.033 --> 48:31.533
(George crying)

48:32.966 --> 48:35.033
I wished for some air
and I heard George crying.

48:35.033 --> 48:36.833
And you brought him back here?
Why?

48:36.833 --> 48:38.166
To bring him comfort.

48:38.166 --> 48:39.700
Edward, you're frightening him.

48:39.700 --> 48:41.333
Please do not harm him.

48:41.333 --> 48:42.833
Return him
to his mother.

48:42.833 --> 48:44.300
I would never harm him!

48:44.300 --> 48:45.700
I'm comforting him!

48:45.700 --> 48:47.500
LADY DENHAM:
Esther, give him to his mother.

48:47.500 --> 48:49.433
Now, please.

48:49.433 --> 48:50.900
(George wailing)

48:50.900 --> 48:52.133
(softly):
Esther.

48:57.600 --> 49:01.133
♪ ♪

49:01.766 --> 49:05.200
(George quiets down)

49:08.700 --> 49:12.800
(George fussing softly)

49:17.666 --> 49:20.600
Lucy and I married young.

49:20.600 --> 49:23.933
I had not long
inherited this house.

49:23.933 --> 49:25.833
She wanted to stay in London,

49:25.833 --> 49:31.266
at the heart of society,
and I did not.

49:31.266 --> 49:34.533
So I came back here.

49:34.533 --> 49:36.933
She stayed for a final season.

49:36.933 --> 49:40.866
And that's where
she met Colonel Lennox.

49:40.866 --> 49:43.400
Captain, as he then was.

49:45.900 --> 49:48.066
I never thought what strangers
she and I had become.

49:49.166 --> 49:54.466
She wrote, delaying her return,
pleading illness.

49:54.466 --> 49:58.000
Months went by
without a word.

49:58.000 --> 50:02.000
At last, my curiosity
conquered my pride.

50:02.000 --> 50:04.166
I went to London.

50:07.466 --> 50:11.600
Only to find she was with child.

50:11.600 --> 50:13.700
His child?

50:16.900 --> 50:20.033
♪ ♪

50:20.033 --> 50:23.566
COLBOURNE:
He'd abandoned her.

50:26.633 --> 50:30.366
And she was too scared
and ashamed to face me.

50:31.933 --> 50:33.800
I showed her no pity.

50:33.800 --> 50:35.166
No compassion.

50:35.166 --> 50:36.466
You bear no blame.

50:36.466 --> 50:40.333
The words I spoke
torment me to this day.

50:44.100 --> 50:48.233
She became a ghost
of her former self.

50:48.233 --> 50:51.400
And not long after
the child was born, she...

50:54.200 --> 50:56.300
Go on.

50:56.300 --> 51:00.600
Lucy knew she wasn't strong.

51:00.600 --> 51:02.100
When she walked out
into the rain that night,

51:02.100 --> 51:03.933
she must have known.

51:06.200 --> 51:09.000
That is why it pains you to be
in Leo's company.

51:12.100 --> 51:16.933
She is a living reminder.

51:16.933 --> 51:22.733
♪ ♪

51:22.733 --> 51:24.066
I so wanted to tell you,

51:24.066 --> 51:27.133
but I was afraid of
what you would think of me.

51:27.133 --> 51:31.500
You should not endure such
recrimination after so long.

51:31.500 --> 51:32.866
Forgive yourself.

51:32.866 --> 51:34.233
I cannot.

51:34.233 --> 51:35.366
I, I cannot...

51:35.366 --> 51:37.666
You must.

51:37.666 --> 51:40.100
Else the past will
thwart the future.

51:42.300 --> 51:46.366
A future that I imagine
could be very dear, indeed.

51:48.300 --> 51:52.666
♪ ♪

52:16.533 --> 52:17.633
♪ ♪

52:17.633 --> 52:19.100
ARTHUR:
Sidney's possessions.

52:19.100 --> 52:21.000
GEORGIANA:
What is it?

52:21.000 --> 52:23.933
ALISON:
Is it not peculiar how we can be
strangers to our own affections?

52:23.933 --> 52:25.100
Miss Heywood.

52:25.100 --> 52:26.933
AUGUSTA:
What is it that you are

52:26.933 --> 52:29.133
frightened of, Uncle?
Go to her.

52:29.133 --> 52:30.200
TOM:
Charlotte,

52:30.200 --> 52:32.300
a Mr. Colbourne
is here to see you.

52:32.300 --> 52:34.566
♪ ♪

